FEEDER LINE OWNERSHIP AGREEMENT THIS FEEDER LINE OWNERSHIP AGREEMENT (this “Agreement”) is entered into as of the 1st day of October, 2003 (the “Effective Date”), by and between COLORADO GREEN HOLDINGS, LLC, a Delaware limited liability company, (“Colorado Green”) and BUTTE CREEK EXPANSION, LLC, a Delaware limited liability company (“Butte Creek”). Each of the foregoing is sometimes referred to in this Agreement in the singular as an “Owner” and in the plural as the “Owners.” RECITALS A. GE Wind Energy LLC, a Delaware limited liability company (“GE Wind”) and Colorado Wind Ventures, LLC (“CWV”) have entered into a Purchase and Sale Agreement, dated October 1, 2003 (the “Purchase and Sale Agreement”) pursuant to which CWV acquired and GE Wind transferred to CWV all of the membership interests in Colorado Green. B. Colorado Green owns certain assets to be used in the construction, ownership and operation of a wind energy project located in Prowers County, Colorado (the “Project”). C. GE Wind and Colorado Green are parties to a First Amended and Restated Agreement to Engineer, Procure and Construct Wind Energy Generation System (the “EPC Agreement”) pursuant to which GE Wind will construct the Project on real property subject to easements held by Colorado Green. D. The Project includes an approximately 44 mile 230 kV transmission line that will be or has been constructed by GE Wind pursuant to the EPC Agreement as part of the Project to carry the electrical output of the Project from the high side of the 34.5kV/230kV breakers at the Project’s 34.5/230 kV substation to the Interconnection Point over related real property easements and fee property interests as set forth in Exhibit A to this Agreement (the “Feeder Line”). E. GE Wind has developed or has acquired certain rights and assets useful or necessary to develop, construct, own and operate an expansion of the Project on a site located in the immediate vicinity of the Project and that will benefit from use of the Feeder Line (the “Expansion Project”). Butte Creek will further develop the Expansion Project. The Expansion Project will be an “eligible facility” within the meaning of Section 32 of the Public Utility Holding Company Act of 1935, as amended. F. The Purchase and Sale Agreement provides for Colorado Green and Butte Creek to enter into this Agreement providing for the joint ownership of the Feeder Line. AGREEMENT The Parties, therefore, agree as follows: 1. Definitions. 1“Affiliate” of any Owner shall mean any other person or entity that directly or indirectly, through one or more intermediaries, controls, is controlled by or is under common control with the specified Owner. For the purposes of this definition, “control,” when used with respect to any specified Owner, means the possession of the power to direct the management or policies of the specified Owner, directly or indirectly, whether through the ownership of voting securities, partnership or limited liability company interests, by contract or otherwise. 2“Colorado Green” has the meaning set forth in the Recitals. 3“Effective Date” has the meaning set forth in the Recitals. 4“EPC Agreement” has the meaning set forth in the Recitals. 5“Feeder Line” has the meaning set forth in the Recitals. 6“Feeder Line Manager” has the meaning set forth in Section 6(a). 7“Feeder Line Easements” means any easements or other land rights (including, without limitation, property owned in fee by the Owners) required for the Feeder Line, including but not limited to any roadways existing at the time of this Agreement or that are in the future constructed on the real property subject to the Feeder Line Easements. 8“FERC” means the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission. 9“Full Capacity” means the designed four hundred (400) MW capacity of the Feeder Line or such lesser capacity (expressed in MW units) as is determined to be the functional total capacity of the Feeder Line following appropriate testing upon its completion. 10“GDPIPD” means Gross Domestic Product Implicit Price Deflator. 11“Interconnection Point” means a physical point between the Lamar substation and the last Feeder Line transmission pole located immediately outside the Lamar substation, located approximately thirty-two (32) miles from the Project substation, as such Interconnection Point is further described in the First Amendment to the Interconnection Agreement between PSCo and Colorado Green, dated September 22, 2003. 12“MW” means a unit of power equal to one megawatt. 13“MW Connection Ratio” has the meaning set forth in Section 4, and as initially set forth in Exhibit B. 14“Owner” and “Owners” means individually or collectively, as appropriate, Colorado Green, Butte Creek and their respective successors and permitted assigns pursuant to Article 13. 15“Owners Committee” means the committee consisting of members designated by the Owners and established pursuant to Article 5. 16“Ownership Interest” has the meaning set forth in Section 2(a). 17“PPM” means PPM Energy, Inc. 18“Project Site” means the point of origin of the Feeder Line furthest from the Lamar substation of PSCo. 19“Prudent Utility Practice” means those practices, methods, acts and standards, as changed from time to time, that 20when engaged in, are commonly used in prudent engineering, contracting and operations to design, construct and operate utility equipment and facilities similar to the Feeder Line lawfully and with safety, reliability, efficiency, expedition and economy, or 21in the exercise of reasonable judgment considering the facts known when engaged in, could have been expected to achieve the desired result consistent with applicable law, safety, reliability, efficiency, expedition and economy. Prudent Utility Practice is not limited to the optimum practices, methods, acts or standards, but includes a spectrum of possible practices, methods, acts or standards. 22“PSCo” means Public Service Company of Colorado. 23“Purchase and Sale Agreement” has the meaning set forth in the Recitals. 24“Transferring Party” means any Owner selling, assigning or otherwise transferring any of its rights or interests in the Feeder Line or the Feeder Line Easements pursuant to Article 13. 2. Ownership of the Feeder Line and Feeder Line Easements . Subject to the terms and conditions of this Agreement, the ownership of the Feeder Line and Feeder Line Easements shall be as follows: (a) As of the Effective Date, Colorado Green shall hold an undivided Ownership Interest in the Feeder Line equal to the ratio of one hundred sixty-two (162) MW to the expected 400 MW capacity of the Feeder Line and Butte Creek shall hold the remaining undivided Ownership Interest (collectively, the “Ownership Interests”). Following appropriate testing upon completion of the Feeder Line, the exact Ownership Interests of the Parties will be determined as follows: if the Full Capacity of the Feeder Line is 400 MW or less, Colorado Green shall hold an undivided Ownership Interest in the Feeder Line equal to the ratio of one hundred sixty-two (162) MW to Full Capacity and Butte Creek shall hold the remaining undivided Ownership Interest. For example, if the Full Capacity is determined to be 400 MW, the Ownership Interest of Colorado Green will be forty and one-half percent (40.5%) and the Ownership Interest of Butte Creek will be fifty-nine and one-half percent (59.5%). If the Full Capacity is determined to be 360 MW, the Ownership Interest of Colorado Green will be forty-five percent (45%) and the Ownership Interest of Butte Creek will be fifty-five percent (55%). If the Full Capacity is determined to be in excess of 400 MW, the Parties’ Ownership Interests in the Feeder Line will be the same if the Full Capacity were 400 MW, i.e. Colorado Green will have an Ownership Interest of forty and one-half percent (40.5%) and Butte Creek will have an Ownership Interest of fifty-nine and one-half percent (59.5%). Colorado Green and Butte Creek also shall each hold equal and undivided interests in the Feeder Line Easements as tenants in common. (b) Each Owner shall promptly take such action (including, but not limited to, the execution, acknowledgment, delivery and recordation of documents and instruments) as may reasonably be requested by any other Owner to effect, evidence or vest each Owner’s respective Ownership Interest in the Feeder Line and Feeder Line Easements or to evidence the transfer by such other Owner of any of its Ownership Interest in the Feeder Line and the Feeder Line Easements. (c) This ownership structure is not organized with the intention or expectation of producing revenue or making a profit from the operation of the Feeder Line but merely as an ownership form through which the Owners can accomplish their purpose of owning, operating and making the Feeder Line available for the use of the Owners. As the Feeder Line is intended solely to transmit electrical power generated by the wind energy facilities of each Owner, all of which will be eligible facilities within the meaning of Section 32 of the Public Utility Holding Company Act of 1935, the Owners do not intend or expect that the Feeder Line or the Feeder Line Easements by themselves will generate any revenue or profit. At no time shall the Feeder Line be used by any person other than an Owner. Subject to the rights of each Owner under Article 13 in the event of the possible sale or other disposition of its Ownership Interest in the Feeder Line and Feeder Line Easements or under Article 17 in the event all or a portion of the Feeder Line is removed from service, the Owners do not expect to receive any material amount of revenue from the Feeder Line. 3. Feeder Line Use . Each Owner shall be entitled to use the Feeder Line capacity to transmit electricity bidirectionally from and to wind energy facility projects owned or controlled by such Owner in an amount up to its Ownership Interest multiplied by the Full Capacity of the Feeder Line. Each Owner covenants not at any time to interconnect with the Feeder Line electric generation facilities with an aggregate capacity that exceeds such Owner’s Ownership Interest multiplied by the Full Capacity of the Feeder Line. If at any time the Feeder Line Manager advises the Owners that in accordance with Prudent Utility Practice the Feeder Line temporarily must be curtailed to transmission at a rate lower than its Full Capacity, Colorado Green’s right to use one hundred sixty-two (162) MW of Feeder Line capacity shall have priority over the rights of other Owners of the Feeder Line, and the other Owners shall curtail their use of the Feeder Line capacity pro-rata to their relative Ownership Interests, in an amount equal to any reduction in total Feeder Line capacity specified by the Feeder Line Manager, for such period as is specified as the period of necessary curtailment by the Feeder Line Manager. 4. Operation and Maintenance of the Feeder Line . Each Owner shall pay its allocated share of all costs of operating and maintaining the Feeder Line and of maintaining the Feeder Line Easements, as such costs are established and approved by the Owners Committee and the Feeder Line Manager, subject to each Owner’s rights of approval and disapproval as set forth in Sections 5 and 6. Each Owner’s allocation of such costs shall be proportional to the ratio of the nameplate MW of capacity wind turbine generation of such Owner connected such as to be capable of transferring electricity onto the Feeder Line, from time to time, to the total nameplate MW capacity of wind turbine generation all Owners then have connected to the Feeder Line (“MW Connection Ratio”). 5. Owners Committee . (a) There is hereby established an Owners Committee to take all actions with respect to the Feeder Line and Feeder Line Easements, except as otherwise provided in Section 5(m), and to take all other actions that all of the Owners may, from time to time, agree in writing that the Owners Committee is authorized to take in connection with the ownership, rebuilding, operation, maintenance, repair, replacement and removal of the Feeder Line and the improvement and maintenance of the Feeder Line Easements, or any portion thereof. Each Owner (or its successors and assigns, acting collectively) shall be entitled to appoint one (1) member to the Owners Committee, provided that no Owner shall be entitled to appoint or maintain a member on the Owners Committee unless that Owner has commenced using the Feeder Line to transmit the output of one or more wind turbines. Each member of the Owners Committee shall be entitled to cast votes proportional to its MW Connection Ratio. Each member of the Owners Committee shall have the right to cast such vote with respect to any decision, approval or other action to be made by the Owners Committee pursuant to this Agreement. If an Owners Committee member participating in a meeting of the Owners Committee does not vote either in favor of or against any matter subject to a decision, approval or other action of the Owners Committee pursuant to this Agreement, such member shall be deemed to have voted in favor. (b) The members of the Owners Committee, as well as alternate members who may represent their respective Owners in the absence of the regular member, are identified on Exhibit C to this Agreement. Any Owner (or its successors and assigns, acting collectively) may change its Owners Committee member by giving written notice of such change to each other Owner, and upon receipt of such notice the Owners shall revise Exhibit C to this Agreement accordingly. Any Owner (or its successors and assigns, acting collectively), by giving written notice to each other Owner, may, for purposes of any decision, approval or other action to be made by the Owners Committee pursuant to this Agreement, appoint an alternate or alternates to serve on the Owners Committee in the place of, and to cast the vote of, the regular Owners Committee member appointed by such Owner. (c) The Owners Committee shall meet regularly, but not less often than once each year, at such time and place as may be agreed upon by the members of the Owners Committee, and the Owners Committee shall meet at such other times and places as may be requested by any Owners Committee member by written notice to each other Owners Committee member at least thirty (30) days prior to such meeting. Members of the Owners Committee may participate in such meetings in person or by means of conference telephone calls or similar communications during which all persons participating in the meeting can hear each other. Participation in a meeting by means of conference telephone calls or similar communications shall be deemed to constitute presence in person at the meeting. Failure by any Owners Committee member to attend any annual or special meeting of the Owners Committee for which notice was properly given under this Section 5(c) shall not invalidate such meeting or any decisions, approvals or other actions taken at such meeting, and the non-attending member shall be deemed to have been present for purposes of a quorum and to have voted in favor of any matter subject to a vote by the Owners Committee at such meeting. (d) The Owners Committee may appoint such subcommittees as it deems necessary or appropriate and, by the unanimous vote of all of the members of the Owners Committee, may delegate approval authority to such subcommittees with respect to matters concerning the Feeder Line and the Feeder Line Easements. Members of a subcommittee are not required to otherwise be a member of the Owners Committee. (e) Any decisions, approvals and other actions that may be taken at a meeting of the Owners Committee may be taken without a meeting if all Owners Committee members consent thereto in writing. The Owners Committee may, by the unanimous vote of the members of the Owners Committee, adopt written procedures for review or approval of matters or for the taking of other actions concerning the Feeder Line and the Feeder Line Easements. (f) Decisions, approvals and other actions of the Owners Committee shall require the approval of a majority of the votes the Owners are entitled to cast; provided that any decision (A) to remove from service permanently or otherwise to dispose of the Feeder Line, or (B) to make any capital expenditure for the purpose of increasing the Full Capacity of the Feeder Line, (C) to enter into any contract with an Affiliate of an Owner, if costs under such contract are to be allocated to the Owners hereunder, or (D) to incur or to authorize the Feeder Line Manager to incur any indebtedness related to the Feeder Line that the Owners would be obligated to repay pursuant to this Agreement, must be approved by the unanimous vote of the Owners Committee. (g) The Owners Committee shall have the authority to review and approve or amend the annual budgets and budget amendments prepared by the Feeder Line Manager pursuant to Section 6(c)(i). If for any reason the Owners Committee does not approve an annual budget prior to the end of the eleventh (11th) month of the preceding operating year, the budget for such preceding operating year shall apply to such operating year, subject to an increase or decrease in such budget to reflect the change in the GDPIPD for all goods and services during the twelve-(12) month period ending with the tenth (10th) month of such preceding operating year. The Owners Committee shall have the authority to amend or replace any Feeder Line budget. (h) If more than ten percent (10%) or more of the votes the Owners are entitled to cast disapproves any item that is adopted by a majority vote of the Owners Committee pursuant to this Article 5, the disapproving Owner shall, within seven (7) days of such disapproving vote (i) segregate such items so that the exact differences are identified and (ii) state in writing the reasons for disapproval and the alternative or alternatives acceptable to the disapproving Owner. The written notice of disapproval shall be provided to the Feeder Line Manager and shall be referred to negotiation pursuant to Section 5(i). In the event any disapproving Owner fails to provide the written notice referenced above within seven (7) days, the disapproval shall be deemed waived and all items in question shall be deemed approved by such Owner. (i) In the event of any notice provided within the seven- (7) day period identified at Section 5(h), a panel of senior executives representing each of the Owners shall be convened within twenty-one (21) days to review the disputes and recommended alternatives of the Owner or Owners providing such notice. In addition, in the event of any other dispute among the Owners related to this Agreement or the performance thereof, a panel of senior executives representing each of such disputing Owners shall be convened prior to any arbitration of such dispute pursuant to Article 9. The senior executives shall establish appropriate procedures for evaluation of and response to the written notice and shall undertake every reasonable effort to resolve disputes by, between and among the Owners by unanimous consent and without the need for formal arbitration. Only in the event the panel of senior representatives is unable to reach agreement for the resolution of issues identified by the notice shall such notice be referred to arbitration in accord with the provisions of Article 9. (j) The Owners may, by unanimous consent, modify or overrule any determination of an arbitrator made pursuant to Article 9, and such decision to modify or overrule such determination shall be effective prospectively or retroactively as specified by the Owners. (k) The Feeder Line Manager shall have the right but not the duty to proceed with an item that has been disapproved as provided in this Section, if the Feeder Line Manager determines in its reasonable judgment that such action is required to avoid an imminent threat of loss of life or property or is required to avoid an imminent threat of interruption of service over the Feeder Line; provided, however, that if the Feeder Line Manager takes such action on a disapproved item and if the determination made by the arbitrator (as modified or overruled pursuant to Section 5(j)) is that the item was not consistent with Prudent Utility Practice, then the Feeder Line Manager shall individually compensate the disapproving Owners for all of the net increase in cost or other financial impact of such action to the extent that it is inconsistent with what the arbitrator determined (as modified or overruled pursuant to Section 5(j)) would under such circumstances have met such test. (l) No member of the Owners Committee shall disapprove (i) items submitted to such member pursuant to the terms of this Agreement that such member did not disapprove within the time allowed, (ii) items previously found by the arbitrator to be consistent with Prudent Utility Practice, or (iii) items the cost of which are not borne by the Owner represented by the disapproving member. (m) Each of the Owners shall, to the extent permitted by Section 761 of the Internal Revenue Code of 1986, as amended (the “Code”), elect as provided in Treasury Regulation Section 1.7612 to exclude from the provisions of Subchapter K of the Code any organization that they may otherwise comprise by virtue of this Agreement. 6. Feeder Line Management. (a) Colorado Green shall be the Feeder Line Manager, subject to Colorado Green’s right to resign as Feeder Line Manager. If Colorado Green (or any other entity) resigns as Feeder Line Manager or if Colorado Green (or any other entity) is removed as Feeder Line Manager for cause, a successor Feeder Line Manager shall be selected by the Owners Committee. In addition, any Owner may call for a vote for removal of Feeder Line Manager for cause, which cause would include negligence that has a material adverse effect on the operation or maintenance of the Feeder Line or the Feeder Line Easements. (b) The Feeder Line Manager shall, as agent of and on behalf of each of the Owners: (i) Operate and maintain (or provide for the operation and maintenance of) the Feeder Line, maintain the Feeder Line Easements (including all roads located thereon), in accord with Prudent Utility Practice, any applicable laws, the terms of any Feeder Line Easements, any applicable interconnection agreements to which an Owner is a party, and commercially reasonable terms included in any insurance policies covering the Feeder Line or the Feeder Line Easements and of which the Feeder Line Manager has received notice. In connection with such operation and maintenance, the Feeder Line Manager is authorized to interrupt service on the Feeder Line and to require curtailments of Feeder Line usage, in accordance with Prudent Utility Practice and in compliance with the terms of this Agreement; provided that the Feeder Line Manager shall give at least twenty-four (24) hours prior written notice to the Owner of any planned or scheduled interruption or curtailment; (ii) Prepare annual budgets and budget amendments as required with respect to the Feeder Line and the Feeder Line Easements, and present such budgets and budget amendments for review and approval by the Owners Committee; (iii) Maintain books and records related to the Feeder Line and the Feeder Line Easements in accordance with generally acceptable accounting practices applicable to the electric utility industry and make such books and records available to each of the Owners upon the request of such Owner during the Feeder Line Manager’s regular business hours and shall otherwise deal with the Feeder Line and the Feeder Line Easements as required by Article 7; (iv) Procure policies of insurance pursuant to Article 8; (v) Perform, in accordance with Prudent Utility Practice, such other duties as may be specified by the Owners Committee; (vi) Execute such contracts and other documents as are necessary or appropriate to carry out the duties enumerated in Sections 6(b)(i) through 6(b)(iv); and (vii) Upon the request of any Owner, promptly provide to such Owner a statement, in such detail as may be reasonably requested by such Owner, of the amounts payable or reimbursable by such Owner pursuant to Section 6(d); and (viii) Review any proposal by an Owner to interconnect generation facilities to the Feeder Line and confirm that the total capacity of all such generation facilities will not in the aggregate exceed such Owner’s Ownership Interest multiplied by the Full Capacity of the Feeder Line. If the Feeder Line Manager determines that any Owner plans to interconnect generation facilities with the Feeder Line in contravention of such Owner’s covenant limiting such interconnection as set out in Section 3, or if any Owner fails to provide the Feeder Line Manager with sufficient information to make such determination, the Feeder Line Manager shall report such efforts to all other Owners and shall take all necessary actions to prevent such interconnection. Each Owner agrees to indemnify and hold the Feeder Line Manager harmless, and waives any claim against the Feeder Line Manager, for any action taken in good faith pursuant to this Section 6(b)(viii). (c) To the extent included in an annual budget or a budget amendment approved and effective pursuant to Sections 5(g) through 5(l) of this Agreement, as well as any additional cost incurred by the Feeder Line Manager and upheld pursuant to Section 5(k), each of the Owners shall reimburse to the Feeder Line Manager an amount proportionate to its MW Connection Ratio, of (i) the salaries, wages and related indirect and overhead costs properly allocable to the Feeder Line for the Feeder Line Manager’s personnel who perform the duties and obligations of the Feeder Line Manager pursuant to this Agreement and (ii) the reasonable payments by the Feeder Line Manager to third parties related to or in connection with the carrying out of the duties and obligations of the Feeder Line Manager pursuant to this Agreement. The Feeder Line Manager will not be entitled to recovery with respect to any indirect costs or payments (including, without limitation, pursuant to any judgment, decree, injunction, order or decision by any governmental authority) incurred or owing by the Feeder Line Manager as a result of or in connection with any mistake, action, inaction or omission constituting gross negligence, fraud or willful or wanton misconduct by the Feeder Line Manager. (d) The payment of any reimbursement pursuant to Section 6(c) shall be as follows: (i) Not later than thirty (30) days after the end of each calendar month (or such other billing period as is agreed by the Owners), the Feeder Line Manager shall mail to each Owner a statement showing the computation in reasonable detail of the amount due to the Feeder Line Manager pursuant to Section 6(c), along with such receipts, documents, and other information in connection with each such statement as may reasonably show the basis for individual billings, charges, and cost computations, up to the date of such statement. The Feeder Line Manager shall promptly provide to each Owner such receipts, documents and other information in connection with each such statement as such Owner may reasonably request. Within thirty (30) days after receipt of each such statement, each Owner shall make a report in writing to the Feeder Line Manager of any dispute concerning such statement, and each Owner shall pay to the Feeder Line Manager any amount undisputed by such Owner set forth in such statement. Any dispute concerning a statement shall be resolved by binding arbitration in accordance with the provisions of Article 9. Such payment shall be made by each Owner to the Feeder Line Manager in immediately available funds by electronic wire transfer, or by deposit otherwise made within three (3) business days after delivery of the arbitrator’s written determination, into the account designated in writing from time to time by the Feeder Line Manager for such purpose. (ii) Notwithstanding the provisions of Section 6(d)(i) above, the Feeder Line Manager shall make available during regular business hours, for inspection and audit by each of the Owners, all books and records of the Feeder Line Manager relating to the amounts contained in each statement provided to such Owner pursuant to Section 6(d)(i). Each Owner shall have the right to conduct such audits with respect to any statement for two (2) years following receipt of such statement. (iii) The Feeder Line Manager also shall permit any Owner to inspect the Feeder Line facilities and the Feeder Line Easements during regular business hours, provided that such Owner arranges such inspection with the Feeder Line Manager and complies with the safety requirements imposed by the Feeder Line Manager. (e) Except as provided in Section 5(k), neither the Feeder Line Manager nor the officers, directors, agents, and employees of the Feeder Line Manager shall be liable pursuant to this Agreement except for acts or omissions constituting gross negligence, fraud, or willful or wanton misconduct. 7. Accounting and Reports . The Feeder Line Manager shall maintain up-to-date books and records of all financial and commercial transactions by the Feeder Line Manager with respect to the Feeder Line and the Feeder Line Easements. Such books and records shall be retained by the Feeder Line Manager for such period as the Owners Committee may determine, but not less than the period provided for by FERC guidelines; and such books and records shall be made available by the Feeder Line Manager for inspection and audit by each of the Owners during the Feeder Line Manager’s regular business hours. The costs and expenses of any inspection or audit requested by an Owner shall be borne by the Owner requesting such inspection or audit. 8. Insurance. (a) The Feeder Line Manager shall procure at the earliest practicable time and thereafter maintain in effect at all times hereinafter provided, to the extent such insurance is reasonably available at reasonable cost, under policies of insurance to protect and insure against: worker’s compensation and employer’s liability, where appropriate; commercial general liability for bodily injury and property damage; all risks of physical damage to property or equipment, including transportation and installation perils; automobile liability; and such other insurance as the Owners Committee may deem necessary. (b) Each Owner shall ensure that each of its policies of insurance that may be applicable to any claims arising in connection with the Feeder Line or the Feeder Line Easements shall provide a waiver, in form and substance reasonably satisfactory to each of the Owners, of the insurer’s rights of subrogation against each other Owner, its successors and assigns, and the respective members, directors, officers, agents, employees and representatives of each such other Owner and its successors and assigns. To the extent permitted by its insurance policies, each Owner waives any right of subrogation against each other Owner, its successors and assigns, and the respective members, directors, officers, agents, employees and representatives of such Owner and its successors and assigns, for losses, costs, damages and expenses arising out of the ownership, rebuilding, operation, maintenance, repair, replacement or removal of the Feeder Line. (c) A copy of all policies of insurance procured by the Feeder Line Manager pursuant to Section 8(a) shall be provided to each Owner. Upon request of an Owner, each Owner shall provide written evidence of each insurer’s waiver of subrogation as required in Section 8(b). The Feeder Line Manager shall notify each Owner in writing of (i) the assertion of any claim in an amount of twenty-five thousand dollars ($25,000) or greater related to the Feeder Line or the Feeder Line Easements immediately following the Feeder Line Manager’s knowledge of any such assertion and (ii) the Feeder Line Manager’s knowledge of the occurrence of an event likely, in the reasonable determination of the Feeder Line Manager, to result in the assertion of such a claim immediately following any such occurrence. All claims for lesser amounts shall be reported in writing annually by the Feeder Line Manager to each Owner. If any loss, damage or impairment to the Feeder Line or Feeder Line Easements occurs, the Feeder Line Manager shall apply the proceeds of any insurance policy with respect thereto to repair, replace or restore the Feeder Line and the Feeder Line Easements to their prior condition. The insurance policies and coverages required to be procured pursuant to this Article 8 shall be reviewed annually by the Owners Committee. (d) Notwithstanding the foregoing provisions of this Section 8, to the extent that any commercial lender providing financing to Colorado Green or Butte Creek or their successors or assigns has specific requirements for insurance of the Feeder Line, the insurance policies maintained for the Feeder Line will comply with those requirements. 9. Arbitration. (a) Except as provided in Section 11(f), any disapproval by an Owner pursuant to Section 5(h) or any other dispute arising under this Agreement, which disapproval or dispute is not resolved pursuant to Section 5(i) of this Agreement, shall be resolved by arbitration pursuant to this Article 9. (b) Upon written notice by representatives of one or more of the Owners to all other Owners that no accord has been reached within thirty (30) days after convening the panel of senior executives provided for in Section 5(i), an arbitrator having expertise in the matter subject to arbitration shall be selected by mutual agreement among the Owners within ten (10) days. If the Owners cannot agree upon selection of an arbitrator within such ten- (10) day period, then any Owner may request the appointment by the American Arbitration Association of an arbitrator having demonstrated expertise in the matter subject to arbitration. (c) An arbitrator selected pursuant to this Article 9 shall establish appropriate time frames for the submittal of written materials by all interested parties concerning the matter subject to arbitration, or the presentation of testimonial evidence or other presentation of evidence or argument at a hearing before such arbitrator, and shall promptly render a written determination resolving and finally determining all matters that are the subject of the arbitration. In particular, whenever any disapproval pursuant to Section 5(h) is referred to the arbitrator: (i) The arbitrator shall approve the Feeder Line Manager’s recommendation if the arbitrator finds (1) that the recommendation is consistent with Prudent Utility Practice and (2) if the matter is a payment item to the Feeder Line Manager (including for the Feeder Line Manager’s allocated indirect and overhead costs), that the payment as recommended by the Feeder Line Manager provides a recovery of such costs as the Feeder Line Manager reasonably incurred. (ii) If the Feeder Line Manager’s recommendation is rejected by the arbitrator by application of the standards set forth in Section 9(c)(i) above, the arbitrator shall approve an alternative recommendation of a disapproving Owner if the arbitrator finds (1) that such recommendation is consistent with Prudent Utility Practice and (2) if the matter is a payment item to the Feeder Line Manager (including of the Feeder Line Manager’s allocated indirect and overhead costs), that such alternative payment provides a recovery of such costs as the Feeder Line Manager reasonably incurred. (iii) In the event that (a) the arbitrator rejects both the recommendation of the Feeder Line Manager and any alternative recommendation of a disapproving Owner, or (b) such dispute does not relate to a specific Feeder Line Manager recommendation and the arbitrator rejects the recommendations of all Owners, the arbitrator shall determine an alternative resolution of the matter in dispute that is in the arbitrator’s judgment (1) appropriate to the subject matter of the arbitration, (2) consistent with Prudent Utility Practice and (3) if the matter is a payment item to the Feeder Line Manager (including of the Feeder Line Manager’s allocated indirect and overhead costs), that provides a recovery of such costs as the Feeder Line Manager reasonably incurred. (d) All proceedings conducted pursuant to this Article 9 shall be in accord with the rules of the American Arbitration Association, except as modified herein. Any hearings, if required with respect to the matters arbitrated, shall be held in Denver, Colorado. Any arbitrator appointed pursuant to this Article 9 shall render decisions expressly in accord with the terms of this Agreement and in writing, using the arbitrator’s best efforts to render such decisions and determinations not later than thirty (30) days after such matters have been submitted to the arbitrator. (e) Written decisions of arbitrators appointed pursuant to this Article 9 shall be conclusive and binding upon all Owners and shall be enforceable by any Owner in any court of competent jurisdiction, except as otherwise provided for in Section 5(j). Determinations of the arbitrator shall become effective immediately and shall remain in effect unless modified or overruled pursuant to Section 5(j). ASSIGNMENT AND ASSUMPTION AGREEMENT AND BILL OF SALE This Assignment and Assumption Agreement and Bill of Sale (this “Assignment”), dated as of April 27, 2007, is made by and between GE WIND ENERGY, LLC, a Delaware limited liability company (“GE Wind”), BUTTE CREEK EXPANSION, LLC, a Delaware limited liability company (“Butte Creek”) and PPM ENERGY, INC., an Oregon corporation (“Assignee”). GE Wind and Butte Creek are referred to herein separately as “Assignor” and, together, as the “Assignors”. WHEREAS, Assignors have developed or acquired (and may develop or acquire additional) rights and assets useful or necessary to develop, construct, own and operate a wind energy project in Prowers County, Colorado (the “Expansion Project”) to be located on those properties described in Schedule F1 attached hereto (the “Expansion Site”) and GE Wind has granted Assignee an option (the “Option”) to purchase those rights and assets pursuant to an Option Agreement dated October 2, 2003 (the “Option Agreement”). WHEREAS, Assignee has exercised the Option and GE Wind and Assignee have entered into that certain Acquisition Agreement, dated as of even date herewith (the “Acquisition Agreement”) pursuant to which Assignors are selling and assigning to Assignee the “Project Assets” as defined in the Acquisition Agreement, including those set forth in Schedule F2. WHEREAS, Assignors now desire to assign to Assignee, and Assignee desires to assume from Assignors, all of Assignors’ right, title and interest in and to the Project Assets, subject to the terms and provisions of this Assignment. NOW, THEREFORE, in consideration of the premises and the mutual agreements herein contained, and for other good and valuable consideration, the receipt and sufficiency of which are hereby acknowledged, the parties hereto agree as follows: 1. Assignment. Assignors hereby grant, convey and assign unto Assignee all right, title and interest of Assignors in, to and under all of the Project Assets to the fullest extent that they are legally assignable, free and clear from any mortgage, deed of trust, lien (choate or inchoate), pledge, charge, security interest, assessment, reservation, assignment, hypothecation, defect in title, encroachment or other burden, restrictive covenant, condition or restriction or easement or encumbrance of any kind or nature whatsoever (collectively “Encumbrances”) other than the Encumbrances listed on Schedule F3 attached hereto (the “Permitted Encumbrances”). This Assignment is governed by and subject to all of the representations, warranties, covenants, indemnities and other terms and conditions of the Acquisition Agreement. 2. Assumption. By accepting this Assignment and by its execution, Assignee hereby accepts the assignment of the Project Assets, and assumes and agrees to perform all of the terms, covenants and conditions of the Project Assets therein that would (except for this Assignment) be required to be performed on the part of an Assignor thereunder from and after the date hereof and not before. 3. Further Assurances. At any time and from time to time after the date hereof, and without further consideration, the parties shall execute and deliver such other instruments and take such other action as either party may reasonably request as necessary or desirable in order to further the purposes of this Assignment and the transactions contemplated hereby. 4. Governing Law. This Assignment shall be governed by and construed in accordance with the laws of the State of New York without regard to principles of conflicts of law. 5. Counterparts. This Assignment may be executed in any number of counterparts, each of which shall be deemed to be an original, but all of which together shall constitute one and the same instrument. IN WITNESS WHEREOF, the parties hereto have executed this Assignment as of the date first above written. COLORADO GREEN HOLDINGS LLC FERC ELECTRIC TARIFF NO. 1
1. Availability. Colorado Green Holdings LLC (“Colorado Green Holdings”) makes electric energy and capacity available under this FERC electric tariff to any purchaser, except as prohibited below. Colorado Green Holdings also makes available, to any purchaser, ancillary services except as prohibited below: a. PJM: Colorado Green Holdings offers regulation and frequency response service, energy imbalance service and operating reserve service (which includes spinning, 10-minute reserves, and 30-minute reserves) for sale into the market administered by PJM Interconnection, L.L.C. (“PJM”) and, where the PJM Open Access Transmission Tariff permits, the self-supply of these services to purchasers for a bilateral sale that is used to satisfy the ancillary services requirements of the PJM Office of Interconnection. b. New York: Colorado Green Holdings offers regulation and frequency response service, and operating reserve service (which includes 10-minute non-synchronous, 30-minute operating reserves, 10-minute spinning reserves, and 10-minute non-spinning reserves) for sale to purchasers in the market administered by the New York Independent System Operator, Inc. c. New England: Colorado Green Holdings offers regulation and frequency response service (automatic generator control), operating reserve service (which includes 10-minute spinning reserve, 10-minute non-spinning reserve, and 30-minute operating reserve service) to purchasers within the markets administered by the ISO New England, Inc. d. California: Colorado Green Holdings offers regulation service, spinning reserve service, and non-spinning reserve service to the California Independent System Operator Corporation (“CAISO”) and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to the CAISO. e. MISO. Colorado Green Holdings offers regulation service and operating reserve service (which include 10-minute spinning reserve and 10-minute supplemental reserve) for sale to the Midcontinent Independent System Operator, Inc. (“MISO”) and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to MISO. f. Southwest Power Pool. Colorado Green Holdings offers regulation service and operating reserve service (which include 10-minute spinning reserve and 10-minute supplemental reserve) for sale to the Southwest Power Pool, Inc. (“SPP”) and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to SPP. g. Third Party Ancillary Services. Colorado Green Holdings offers Regulation Service, Reactive Supply and Voltage Control Service, Energy and Generator Imbalance Service, Operating Reserve-Spinning, Operating Reserve-Supplemental, and Primary Frequency Response Service. Sales will not include the following: (1) sales to an RTO or an ISO, i.e., where that entity has no ability to self-supply ancillary services but instead depends on third parties; and (2) sales to a traditional, franchised public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier, or sales where the underlying transmission service is on the system of the public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier. Sales of Operating Reserve-Spinning and Operating Reserve-Supplemental will not include sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except where the Commission has granted authorization. Sales of Regulation Service and Reactive Supply and Voltage Control Service will not include sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except at rates not to exceed the buying public utility transmission provider’s OATT rate for the same service or where the Commission has granted authorization. 2. Applicability. This tariff is applicable to all wholesale sales of electric energy and capacity by Colorado Green Holdings. 3. Rates. Failure to comply with the applicable provisions of 18 C.F.R. Part 35, Subpart H, and with any orders of the Commission concerning Colorado Green Holdings’s market-based rate authority, will constitute a violation of this tariff. 6.
